</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,295,898]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,583,609]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
The new species belongs to the dark 
<taxonomicName box="[744,905,583,609]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis box="[744,817,584,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Druon</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
group (also comprising 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuesta-Porta &amp; Melika &amp; Nicholls &amp; Stone &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2022" box="[1180,1321,583,609]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="alexandri">
<emphasis box="[1180,1321,583,609]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. alexandri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuesta-Porta &amp; Melika &amp; Nicholls &amp; Stone &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="serretae">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. serretae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuesta-Porta &amp; Melika &amp; Nicholls &amp; Stone &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Lyon" baseAuthorityYear="1996" box="[242,423,619,645]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flocculentum">
<emphasis box="[242,423,619,645]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. flocculentum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
) but it is the only species in this group with big ocelli (OOL at least as great as diameter of lateral ocellus (
<figureCitation box="[355,437,655,681]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–49" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[183,1395,934,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-309@23.[173,1414,921,1734]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 46–49. Druon gregori, sp. nov., asexual female. 46–48, head: 46, frontal view, 47, dorsal view, 48, posterior view. 49, antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6520498" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6520498/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
)) and the only species in the genus with the mesonotum 1.3× as broad as long (
<figureCitation box="[1339,1424,655,682]" captionStart="FIGURES 50–53" captionStartId="24.[151,264,1960,1984]" captionTargetBox="[219,1376,680,1922]" captionTargetId="figure-258@24.[193,1395,669,1937]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURES 50–53. Druon gregori, sp. nov., asexual female. 50, mesosoma and propleura, frontal view. 51, mesosoma, lateral view. 52, mesoscutum and mesoscutellum, dorsal view. 53, metascutellum and propodeum, posterodorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6520502" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6520502/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 52</figureCitation>
). Some specimens have the head with genae and lower head rusty brown; these specimens most closely resemble 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuesta-Porta &amp; Melika &amp; Nicholls &amp; Stone &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beutenmuller" baseAuthorityYear="1913" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fullawayi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. fullawayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but differ in having parallel internal margins of eyes (
<figureCitation box="[866,948,727,754]" captionStart="FIGURES 46–49" captionStartId="23.[151,264,1758,1782]" captionTargetBox="[183,1395,934,1722]" captionTargetId="figure-309@23.[173,1414,921,1734]" captionTargetPageId="23" captionText="FIGURES 46–49. Druon gregori, sp. nov., asexual female. 46–48, head: 46, frontal view, 47, dorsal view, 48, posterior view. 49, antenna." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6520498" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6520498/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 46</figureCitation>
) (ventrally convergent in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Cuesta-Porta &amp; Melika &amp; Nicholls &amp; Stone &amp; Pujade-Villar" authorityYear="2022" baseAuthorityName="Beutenmuller" baseAuthorityYear="1913" box="[1238,1376,727,753]" class="Insecta" family="Cynipidae" genus="Druon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fullawayi">
<emphasis box="[1238,1376,727,753]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">D. fullawayi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 20–25" captionStartId="16.[151,264,1928,1952]" captionTargetBox="[156,1430,566,1897]" captionTargetId="figure-219@16.[152,1435,561,1904]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURES 20–25. Druon fullawayi, comb. nov., asexual female. 20–23, head: 20, frontal view, 21, dorsal view, 22, lateral view, 23, posterior view. 24, antenna. 25, mesosoma and propleura, frontal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6520483" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6520483/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
)), the notauli incomplete (
